WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.710 --> 00:00:04.600
&gt;&gt;female presenter: We're very happy today
to welcome Frank Bruni, author of "Born Round:

00:00:04.600 --> 00:00:10.130
A Story of Family, Food and a Ferocious Appetite."
Frank Bruni was named the Restaurant Critic

00:00:10.130 --> 00:00:16.869
for the New York Times in April 2004. Before
then, he was a newspapers Rome bureau chief,

00:00:16.869 --> 00:00:22.470
White House reporter, the lead correspondent
for George W. Bush's 2000 presidential campaign

00:00:22.470 --> 00:00:28.509
and a frequent contributor to the Sunday Times
Magazine. He's the author of the New York

00:00:28.509 --> 00:00:35.149
Times bestseller; "Ambling into History by
George W. Bush" and his restaurant related

00:00:35.149 --> 00:00:38.880
articles for The Times have appeared in each
of the last three editions of the Best Food

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:44.019
Writing in America. He was a finalist for
the Pulitzer Prize in Feature Writing for

00:00:44.019 --> 00:00:49.269
his work before The Times at the Detroit Free
Press and he's currently reporter at large

00:00:49.269 --> 00:00:53.440
for The New York Times and he lives in New
York City. So, please give a warm welcome

00:00:53.440 --> 00:00:54.440
to Frank Bruni.

00:00:54.440 --> 00:00:55.969
[applause]

00:00:55.969 --> 00:01:02.000
&gt;&gt;Frank: Hey. Thanks for, thanks for having
me here. I really appreciate it. This is an

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.740
amazing place. I think my colleague, Maureen
Dowd, came here about a year ago and I remember

00:01:06.740 --> 00:01:10.240
reading her column about Google, but until
you kind of see this whole campus it doesn't

00:01:10.240 --> 00:01:14.579
really, you can't really appreciate what this
is. You guys work in a very charmed, charmed

00:01:14.579 --> 00:01:19.280
environment. I hope everyone's happy here
and likes it. I'll swap, I'll swap The New

00:01:19.280 --> 00:01:21.119
York Times for Google with you any day.

00:01:21.119 --> 00:01:24.500
Cynthia said, "What kind of perks do you have
at The Times?" And I thought for awhile and

00:01:24.500 --> 00:01:29.509
I realized none. We have, we have the pleasure
of saying you work for The New York Times

00:01:29.509 --> 00:01:34.829
and sometimes that opens doors, but there's
no free food, there's no gym, no nap, no nap

00:01:34.829 --> 00:01:41.729
stations, none, nothing of the kind. I, about
a year ago, I wrote this book. Well, I wrote

00:01:41.729 --> 00:01:45.909
this earlier, but a year ago this book came
out in hardcover. It's called Born Round.

00:01:45.909 --> 00:01:50.630
In hardcover, it was called The Secret History
of a Full-Time Eater. This, the title has

00:01:50.630 --> 00:01:55.580
now changed. In the soft cover, the subtitle
is A Story of Family, Food and a Ferocious

00:01:55.580 --> 00:02:00.860
Appetite. And it's a book I wrote because
while there, while there were many, many food

00:02:00.860 --> 00:02:05.140
memoirs out there, many of which I've read
over time because it was just a genre I enjoyed,

00:02:05.140 --> 00:02:10.240
I didn't feel like there were any that talked
about the flip-side or the dark side of being

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:11.980
obsessed with food.

00:02:11.980 --> 00:02:17.610
Every food memoir I read everyone just talked
about kind of going into a swoon and falling

00:02:17.610 --> 00:02:22.260
into a field of soft arugula while not upsetting
your champagne flute and the foie gras in

00:02:22.260 --> 00:02:27.620
the background. And almost everybody I met
when I started writing predominantly about

00:02:27.620 --> 00:02:32.470
food, as The New York Times' restaurant critic,
everybody I met in the kind of food journalism

00:02:32.470 --> 00:02:38.670
world was someone who was extremely, extremely
disciplined about their food consumption.

00:02:38.670 --> 00:02:44.230
They were not these wonder people who had
furnace-like metabolisms who never had to

00:02:44.230 --> 00:02:49.510
worry about what they eat. In fact, they were
the most, they were the most kind of vigilant,

00:02:49.510 --> 00:02:54.261
mindful eaters I'd ever met, but no one ever
talked about that as they wrote all of this

00:02:54.261 --> 00:02:58.410
lovely prose that exhorted people to kind
of pull, pull a chair up to the table and

00:02:58.410 --> 00:02:59.410
dig in.

00:02:59.410 --> 00:03:03.880
So, I wanted to write a food memoir. I wanted
to write a book about my relationship with

00:03:03.880 --> 00:03:08.750
food, which was a very unusual one in terms
of the drama and comedy of it that, that kind

00:03:08.750 --> 00:03:12.850
of told a fuller story about what food can
do to people and how food can trip people

00:03:12.850 --> 00:03:18.130
up. I was someone who, in the course of my
life, went on every fad diet there ever was;

00:03:18.130 --> 00:03:23.840
yo-yoed over time, back and forth between
about 180 pounds to about 280 pounds. And

00:03:23.840 --> 00:03:28.070
I thought telling that story from the vantage
point, from the ironic vantage point, of someone

00:03:28.070 --> 00:03:32.890
who ended up making, making eating his profession
made a lot of sense.

00:03:32.890 --> 00:03:37.640
I, I, what I'd mostly like to do today is
just answer questions people have because

00:03:37.640 --> 00:03:41.370
I find everyone has questions about what it's
like to be a restaurant critic, what it's

00:03:41.370 --> 00:03:46.610
like to be The New York Times' restaurant
critic. We can talk about journalism in general,

00:03:46.610 --> 00:03:48.500
Google's effect on it--no, I'm just kidding.

00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:49.500
[laughter]

00:03:49.500 --> 00:03:53.900
We can do whatever, but just to give you a
little bit more of a flavor of the book, I,

00:03:53.900 --> 00:03:58.150
I just thought I'd and to kinda run out the
clock a little bit, I thought I'd just read,

00:03:58.150 --> 00:04:04.971
read one passage. The book goes through pretty
much a whole life told from the vantage point

00:04:04.971 --> 00:04:09.730
of food, but whenever I had little adventures
along the way I tried to put them in here

00:04:09.730 --> 00:04:13.791
if I thought they made for good stories. Right
before I became the restaurant critic, I was

00:04:13.791 --> 00:04:18.269
The Times' Rome bureau chief; that's the title
they use. We have one correspondent in Rome,

00:04:18.269 --> 00:04:19.790
so, you're the bureau chief of one.

00:04:19.790 --> 00:04:20.790
[laughter]

00:04:20.790 --> 00:04:24.840
But that's the title they give you so we use
it and I was covering Italy and Greece and

00:04:24.840 --> 00:04:29.740
the Vatican. And when I went to Italy, I had
just lost an enormous amount of weight and

00:04:29.740 --> 00:04:34.270
people said, "Well, how are you ever gonna
keep it off if you are in Italy?" And so,

00:04:34.270 --> 00:04:38.229
I was looking at Italy, in part, through the,
through the prism of someone who's, "Ok, why

00:04:38.229 --> 00:04:42.680
are all of these people who live in this food
paradise not as fat as the average American?"

00:04:42.680 --> 00:04:47.100
And so a chapter of the book sort of is, is
me going through Italy trying to figure out

00:04:47.100 --> 00:04:52.520
what that's about and, and I just wanted to
read you a little, a little snippet from that

00:04:52.520 --> 00:04:59.430
if I've marked it correctly. Ok, this is in
terms of why aren't Italians fatter than they

00:04:59.430 --> 00:05:00.430
are?

00:05:00.430 --> 00:05:01.430
[reads from book]

00:05:01.430 --> 00:05:05.180
"The answer wasn't exercise. My experience
trying to find and use a proper gym, somewhere

00:05:05.180 --> 00:05:08.900
with the full complements of weights and an
attractive array of cardiovascular machines

00:05:08.900 --> 00:05:14.139
and a setting that blunted the potential drudgery
of it all, made that immediately clear. In

00:05:14.139 --> 00:05:17.510
the center of Rome, where The Times office
was located, there was nothing like a spacious

00:05:17.510 --> 00:05:22.680
gleaming equinox where past illegitimate fitness
centers were the sorts of perfunctory setups

00:05:22.680 --> 00:05:26.870
you found in hotels. They were depressing
and they weren't gonna motivate me to visit

00:05:26.870 --> 00:05:30.939
often or linger for more than a few minutes
at a time. But in a slightly less central

00:05:30.939 --> 00:05:36.969
location, along one edge of the Villa Borghese
Park, was the Roman Sport Forum or La Roman,

00:05:36.969 --> 00:05:42.749
as people in the know called it, speaking
of it as they might La Loren or La Jolie.

00:05:42.749 --> 00:05:46.870
Romans saw it as an ostentatiously endowed
diva of a gym even though it was little larger

00:05:46.870 --> 00:05:50.629
or better outfitted than the kind of health
club you find in any strip mall in any American

00:05:50.629 --> 00:05:52.680
excerpt. It had a modest pool,--

00:05:52.680 --> 00:05:53.780
[clears throat]

00:05:53.780 --> 00:05:58.050
"a weight room with scores of machines, a
glass walled exercise studio for calisthenics

00:05:58.050 --> 00:06:02.530
and perhaps two dozen treadmills, Stairmasters,
recumbent bikes and the like. It was darker

00:06:02.530 --> 00:06:07.120
than any American gym I knew, making me wonder
if Italians considered mood lighting a catalyst

00:06:07.120 --> 00:06:11.740
for working out. I was thinking along the
wrong lines. Working out wasn't really the

00:06:11.740 --> 00:06:17.639
point of La Roman. In fact, the managers of
La Roman seemed intent on preventing it. For

00:06:17.639 --> 00:06:21.919
starters, there was the signed doctor's note
they insisted I get in order not just to join

00:06:21.919 --> 00:06:26.729
the gym, but even to venture as far as the
locker room during an initial visit. I produced

00:06:26.729 --> 00:06:31.259
a note, paid for a six month membership, changed
into my work out clothes and found an available

00:06:31.259 --> 00:06:35.400
treadmill. I had been on it less than five
minutes when I noticed one of the gym attendants

00:06:35.400 --> 00:06:40.509
standing at my side flapping his arms and
yelling at me. "E vietato," he was saying

00:06:40.509 --> 00:06:43.909
and I would soon realize that whether you
were speaking to an attendant at La Roman

00:06:43.909 --> 00:06:48.219
or reading one of the many signs posted on
the walls, that phrase was the most prevalent

00:06:48.219 --> 00:06:55.090
one; a kind of motto for the gym: E vietato.
E vietato, translation: It's forbidden. But

00:06:55.090 --> 00:07:01.599
precisely what about my activity on the treadmill
vietato? Running? All the Italians on the

00:07:01.599 --> 00:07:05.020
treadmills around mine were walking and they
were walking rather slowly at that and nary

00:07:05.020 --> 00:07:09.999
a pinprick of perspiration smudging their
fashionable exercise outfits. My own t-shirt

00:07:09.999 --> 00:07:13.749
was already mottled and wet. So maybe sweating
was vietato.

00:07:13.749 --> 00:07:15.639
[laughter]

00:07:15.639 --> 00:07:19.770
"The attendant explained that while the note
from my doctor entitled me to use the gym's

00:07:19.770 --> 00:07:24.400
pool, weight machines, locker room and, of
course, snack bar, it didn't entitle me to

00:07:24.400 --> 00:07:29.509
use any cardiovascular equipment. For that,
I needed to submit to an independent examination,

00:07:29.509 --> 00:07:34.439
including a stress test with heart monitors
taped to my chest, by the gym's own physician.

00:07:34.439 --> 00:07:38.330
It would cost me a hundred dollars and an
appointment wasn't available until a week

00:07:38.330 --> 00:07:43.499
from then. I bided my time, paid my money,
passed the stress test and returned to the

00:07:43.499 --> 00:07:47.479
treadmill without incident using my gym visits
to run three or so miles on a treadmill and

00:07:47.479 --> 00:07:51.800
spend 30 to 40 minutes lifting weights. In
the weight rooms were signs spelling out,

00:07:51.800 --> 00:07:56.970
for unexplained reasons, that it was vietato
to chew gum. It was vietato to leave free

00:07:56.970 --> 00:08:00.930
weights lying around, a transgression that
might require one of the half dozen attendants

00:08:00.930 --> 00:08:04.819
to do something other than gossip with one
another, haranguing unauthorized treadmill

00:08:04.819 --> 00:08:10.279
users and unwind in the snack bar, which was
a nearly full scale trattoria with seating

00:08:10.279 --> 00:08:14.900
for dozens and a menu that included spaghetti
carbonara and prosciutto e melone.

00:08:14.900 --> 00:08:15.900
[laughter]

00:08:15.900 --> 00:08:19.840
"My path to and from the locker rooms skirted
its tables at which I'd sometimes spot at

00:08:19.840 --> 00:08:25.259
my way out of the gym, the same La Roman staffers
and members I'd spotted on my way in. It apparently

00:08:25.259 --> 00:08:29.450
wasn't vietato for a member of La Roman to
lean against or straddle a weight machine

00:08:29.450 --> 00:08:33.900
for twenty uninterrupted minutes, monopolizing
it without attempting anything more physical

00:08:33.900 --> 00:08:38.630
than the arching of an eyebrow. La Roman members
did this all the time, provided that the weight

00:08:38.630 --> 00:08:42.260
machine in question afforded them a good view
of other patrons and vice versa. Although

00:08:42.260 --> 00:08:46.250
most of them were thin and no small number
of them were gorgeous, their time a La Roman

00:08:46.250 --> 00:08:51.130
deserved little credit for that. I was marveling
one evening at their languorous, even phobic,

00:08:51.130 --> 00:08:55.230
relationship with physical exertion when,
yet again, a flapping yelling gym attendant

00:08:55.230 --> 00:09:00.570
materialized at my side. He spoke in such
rushed, histrionic Italian that I had to implore

00:09:00.570 --> 00:09:05.730
him a half dozen times to slow down, back
up, repeat himself and maybe use fewer polysyllabic

00:09:05.730 --> 00:09:11.390
words. What exactly was il problema? He pointed
to my gym shorts, then grabbed my arm and

00:09:11.390 --> 00:09:16.580
tugged me to a sign I hadn't noticed before.
It explained that it was vietato to wear shorts

00:09:16.580 --> 00:09:18.430
that didn't adhere tightly to your legs.

00:09:18.430 --> 00:09:20.060
[laughter]

00:09:20.060 --> 00:09:24.970
"My shorts didn't and were thus, vietato.
Trust me on this, the shorts I was wearing

00:09:24.970 --> 00:09:29.380
were as unremarkable and unobjectionable as
athletic shorts could be. They were precisely

00:09:29.380 --> 00:09:33.770
the type of shorts: ribbed waist, drawstring,
thick cotton, material reaching halfway down

00:09:33.770 --> 00:09:38.180
the thigh that every college since the dawn
of academia has printed its logo on and sold

00:09:38.180 --> 00:09:43.020
in the student store. They weren't flamboyant
shorts, they weren't tattered shorts, they

00:09:43.020 --> 00:09:47.910
weren't skimpy shorts, they were archetypical,
boring athletic shorts. Why did it matter

00:09:47.910 --> 00:09:52.970
whether they adhered to my legs? I told the
attendant in my flawed, functional Italian

00:09:52.970 --> 00:09:57.180
that for my next visit to the gym I would
get and wear shorts that were adhering or

00:09:57.180 --> 00:10:00.970
adhesive or whatever they were supposed to
be. Then I turned away from him and headed

00:10:00.970 --> 00:10:05.280
to the next weight machine I planned to use.
I felt a tug on my arm; he wouldn't let me

00:10:05.280 --> 00:10:10.530
go. He held up an index finger in the international
signal for "wait a second," and bolted away.

00:10:10.530 --> 00:10:17.220
Within less than a minute he was back with
two thick, blue rubber bands. I'd seen rubber

00:10:17.220 --> 00:10:20.160
bands like these before; they were the kind
often wrapped around the base of a head of

00:10:20.160 --> 00:10:24.220
broccoli and maybe that's where they'd been
at some point. But as he handed them to me,

00:10:24.220 --> 00:10:27.870
I understood that where they were supposed
to be now was wrapped around each two floppy

00:10:27.870 --> 00:10:33.090
leg of my two floppy cotton gym shorts. I
fingered them, looked strangely at them, looked

00:10:33.090 --> 00:10:37.190
strangely at him trying to work some self
pity and pleading into my expression and get

00:10:37.190 --> 00:10:42.340
a pass. He didn't waver. And so I bet to his
will, or rather, snapped to it and spent the

00:10:42.340 --> 00:10:46.840
next 45 minutes stalking La Roman like a human
broccoli; each thigh banded in blue.

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:48.080
[laughter]

00:10:48.080 --> 00:10:51.850
"A few days later I ran into one of my few
acquaintances at the gym and asked him if

00:10:51.850 --> 00:10:56.530
he could shed some light on this floppy shorts
policy. 'You can't wear floppy shorts,' he

00:10:56.530 --> 00:11:02.120
explained, 'because if you did, other people
could see up your legs to your crotch.' 'But

00:11:02.120 --> 00:11:06.370
all they'd see,' I said, 'is my underwear.'
'You don't understand,' he said. 'The problem

00:11:06.370 --> 00:11:10.680
the gym was having was that some people were
short, loose legged shorts and not wearing

00:11:10.680 --> 00:11:14.220
underwear.' He paused and added, 'Deliberately.'

00:11:14.220 --> 00:11:15.500
[laughter]

00:11:15.500 --> 00:11:20.390
"So, now I understood what was actually vietato
was flashing your fellow gym users. And what

00:11:20.390 --> 00:11:25.030
many La Roman regulars most wanted to do wasn't
shoulder presses and a full half hour on the

00:11:25.030 --> 00:11:30.060
elliptical. They wanted to pose, hence the
mood lighting, preen, hence the avoidance

00:11:30.060 --> 00:11:35.000
of perspiration and give their fellow fitness
enthusiasts a gander at the family jewels.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:40.040
That last impulse explained not only the policy
on floppy shorts, but also a sign posted in

00:11:40.040 --> 00:11:44.760
the men's locker room. It stressed that it
was vietato to shower with the door in front

00:11:44.760 --> 00:11:46.080
of your individual stall open."

00:11:46.080 --> 00:11:50.190
[laughter]

00:11:50.190 --> 00:11:53.730
Anyway, I never did quite solve the riddle
fully why Italians aren't as heavy as we are,

00:11:53.730 --> 00:11:57.130
but I think it mostly has to do with portions
and it doesn't have to do with their time

00:11:57.130 --> 00:12:02.201
at La Roman or any other Italian gym I ever
encountered. I'd love to answer any questions

00:12:02.201 --> 00:12:12.180
anybody has about food, restaurants, The New
York Times, or nothing. You had one before.

00:12:12.180 --> 00:12:14.400
[pause]

00:12:14.400 --> 00:12:32.368
&gt;&gt;female audience member #1: I was wondering
if you missed being able to eat for a living?

00:12:32.368 --> 00:12:33.368
I mean, having read your book, I know that
some of the food issues and obsessions that

00:12:33.368 --> 00:12:34.368
you had, I just wondered if you missed that,
like, having the excuse to eat?

00:12:34.368 --> 00:12:36.280
&gt;&gt;Frank: When I was The Times' restaurant
critic, I would eat out seven nights a week.

00:12:36.280 --> 00:12:39.620
Sometimes I would eat two dinners in a row
because you have so much scouting of restaurants

00:12:39.620 --> 00:12:44.330
to do. Every restaurant that we review and
give a star rating to because that rating

00:12:44.330 --> 00:12:49.440
can have such economic consequence the loose
rule of thumb is that you visit it at least

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:53.920
three times. Probably most of the restaurants
I reviewed, I visited four times. So, yeah,

00:12:53.920 --> 00:13:00.610
I had, I had an obligation or definitely this,
this thing that kept me going out. I don't

00:13:00.610 --> 00:13:04.240
miss it in that sense and I don't feel like
I need an excuse to kind of go out or have

00:13:04.240 --> 00:13:08.720
a great meal. I mean, it's something I, I
left to my own devices; it's something I'm

00:13:08.720 --> 00:13:14.800
gonna do anyway. And what's nice is, is not
kind of having to have your schedule determined

00:13:14.800 --> 00:13:19.430
by what the new restaurants are or what you
have to visit two more times before "X" date.

00:13:19.430 --> 00:13:24.980
I just, I find that I can, I can use restaurants
more the way I want to than ever, than I was

00:13:24.980 --> 00:13:29.590
for five and a half years. I can go back to
a given restaurant and keep ordering the same

00:13:29.590 --> 00:13:33.350
dish over and over again because I love it
and that's something that when you're a critic,

00:13:33.350 --> 00:13:37.530
you lose that opportunity. You lose the opportunity
to be a regular at a restaurant, which I think

00:13:37.530 --> 00:13:41.200
is one of the greatest joys of restaurant
going; it's establishing a really nice relationship

00:13:41.200 --> 00:13:45.760
with a favorite place and going again and
again. And restaurant criticism sort of doesn't

00:13:45.760 --> 00:13:47.030
sort of allow for that or really capture that.

00:13:47.030 --> 00:13:48.030
[pause]

00:13:48.030 --> 00:13:52.780
&gt;&gt;female audience member #2: Thanks for joining
us today.

00:13:52.780 --> 00:13:55.660
&gt;&gt;Frank: Thanks for having me.

00:13:55.660 --> 00:13:58.460
&gt;&gt;audience member #2: So, I was curious about
the, the process. So, you're told you have

00:13:58.460 --> 00:14:05.110
to critique a certain restaurant? What do
you do? Do you gather the troops and go a

00:14:05.110 --> 00:14:11.762
few times or kind of, how do you then get
to the point where you're actually writing

00:14:11.762 --> 00:14:12.762
the review?

00:14:12.762 --> 00:14:14.630
&gt;&gt;Frank: You're not really kind of told to
go to a restaurant. You pretty much, you're,

00:14:14.630 --> 00:14:17.940
you're watching the calendar of openings.
Usually, it's pretty obvious what restaurants

00:14:17.940 --> 00:14:22.930
need to be reviewed because they're the restaurants
that, in if Tom Kalikio is opening a new restaurant,

00:14:22.930 --> 00:14:26.480
the public curiosity about that is going to
be intense enough that that's definitely a

00:14:26.480 --> 00:14:30.130
restaurant you're gonna have to review. I
would say two thirds of the restaurants you

00:14:30.130 --> 00:14:36.500
review in a given year fall into that sort
of "no brainer" category. When you, when you

00:14:36.500 --> 00:14:40.240
see a restaurant opening that you, that you
feel you're gonna have the need to review

00:14:40.240 --> 00:14:44.200
and that people have a curiosity about the,
wants, that the curiosity be sated fairly

00:14:44.200 --> 00:14:48.600
quickly, you kind of look at the calendar,
you say, "How, when will that restaurant have

00:14:48.600 --> 00:14:52.450
been open about three, three and a half months?"
Because you don't wanna do it right away cause

00:14:52.450 --> 00:14:56.191
that's not really gonna be an accurate snapshot
of the restaurant. You, you don't really wanna

00:14:56.191 --> 00:15:00.040
visit in the first week or the first two weeks.
Once you figure out like when it's sort of

00:15:00.040 --> 00:15:03.810
ripe to be written about, you kind of work
your way backwards and you stagger a bunch

00:15:03.810 --> 00:15:09.570
of reservations so that on what would be the
due date for your review, you'll have three

00:15:09.570 --> 00:15:13.741
or four visits to the restaurant under your
belt and you'll be able to write. You get

00:15:13.741 --> 00:15:18.500
on the phone, you make a lot of reservations,
you, you learn exactly what that restaurants

00:15:18.500 --> 00:15:22.750
reservation policies are and you make sure
to call at the earliest possible moment because

00:15:22.750 --> 00:15:27.010
you can't afford not to get in because you
need it for your job, but you're calling anonymously

00:15:27.010 --> 00:15:30.950
so you're not pulling strings. And then you
reach out to your friends and in this rubix

00:15:30.950 --> 00:15:34.810
cube of a schedule you construct, you can
decide who you invite to come with you this

00:15:34.810 --> 00:15:37.940
time or that time. Sometimes you leave that
to the last minute, but you almost always

00:15:37.940 --> 00:15:42.720
make a reservation for four because one of
the goals of repeat visits to a restaurant

00:15:42.720 --> 00:15:46.960
is to work your way through the menu. So,
if you're only going alone or with one other

00:15:46.960 --> 00:15:51.490
person, it's very hard to order a variety
of food. And then you keep track of what you

00:15:51.490 --> 00:15:55.640
eat so when you go back a second or third
time, if you've had the salmon twice or you've

00:15:55.640 --> 00:15:59.520
had the rib eye, you don't get that again;
you have a lot of very, very disappointed

00:15:59.520 --> 00:16:02.720
friends who sit down very excited and then
you tell them what they cannot order.

00:16:02.720 --> 00:16:03.910
[laughter]

00:16:03.910 --> 00:16:06.690
And you encounter a lot of long faces and
then you hold up your credit card and say,

00:16:06.690 --> 00:16:09.970
"Remember, I'm paying so it's not really so
bad."

00:16:09.970 --> 00:16:10.970
[laughter]

00:16:10.970 --> 00:16:11.970
That's the process.

00:16:11.970 --> 00:16:12.970
&gt;&gt;audience member #1: Thanks.

00:16:12.970 --> 00:16:13.970
&gt;&gt;Frank: Sure.

00:16:13.970 --> 00:16:15.260
&gt;&gt;female audience member #3: Hi. Thanks for
being here.

00:16:15.260 --> 00:16:16.700
&gt;&gt;Frank: Thanks for having me.

00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:29.350
&gt;&gt;audience member #3: I have lots of questions,
among them, can a hole in the wall restaurant

00:16:29.350 --> 00:16:38.910
get four stars? And two, did, did you wear
disguises like Mimi Sheraton? Three, what

00:16:38.910 --> 00:16:41.890
was it like going from restaurant criticism
back to real journalism? One is so subjective

00:16:41.890 --> 00:16:46.390
and it's a different kind of writing and then
to go back to digging for facts and investigating

00:16:46.390 --> 00:16:50.890
and then to find, I, when you criti-, where
you a critic for two years?

00:16:50.890 --> 00:16:56.450
&gt;&gt;Frank: I was a critic for fi-, five and
a quarter years; five and a half, yeah.

00:16:56.450 --> 00:17:02.740
&gt;&gt;audience member #3: Five and a half, so,
Google had really changed things by the time

00:17:02.740 --> 00:17:06.159
you came back to reporting. So, what was,
what was that like? That's my main question.

00:17:06.159 --> 00:17:08.930
&gt;&gt;Frank: Ok, the, I'll take them in reverse
order because I can remember them that way.

00:17:08.930 --> 00:17:14.329
The "what was it like to go back to quote
unquote real reporting from restaurant criticism,"

00:17:14.329 --> 00:17:18.949
I actually don't see the things as differently
as someone else might. I think where--

00:17:18.949 --> 00:17:19.949
[clears throat]

00:17:19.949 --> 00:17:23.789
while criticism asks you to insert, it doesn't
really ask, it demands that you insert your

00:17:23.789 --> 00:17:28.700
own opinion, I think its foundation is the
gathering of information and evidence. I mean,

00:17:28.700 --> 00:17:33.340
it's I think, the same powers of observation
and analysis that you use when you write a

00:17:33.340 --> 00:17:40.009
profile of a political figure are the ones
you use when you are doing a piece of criticism.

00:17:40.009 --> 00:17:44.029
It's just that at the end of it all and during
the process of it all, you're not trying to

00:17:44.029 --> 00:17:48.539
put your personal feelings to the side, you're
actually trying to kind of almost, almost

00:17:48.539 --> 00:17:53.350
cultivate your personal feelings. But it doesn't,
it's not really, the process isn't that, isn't

00:17:53.350 --> 00:17:57.940
really that different and I don't think the
skills are that different. The Internet change

00:17:57.940 --> 00:18:03.210
has changed restaurant criticism a lot in
the sense that there's now any number of sites

00:18:03.210 --> 00:18:07.440
that, that rely on user generated content.
And so you can go to Yelp--

00:18:07.440 --> 00:18:08.440
[clears throat]

00:18:08.440 --> 00:18:12.470
and you can use that as your restaurant reviewing
resource as opposed to The New York Times.

00:18:12.470 --> 00:18:17.740
I think that, I think that as people get smarter,
they'll see that it's not a substitute though.

00:18:17.740 --> 00:18:22.960
We were talking about this at lunch. You don't
know when you're reading, like you could be

00:18:22.960 --> 00:18:28.480
reading ten Yelp raves for a place all ten
of those may have been planted by the restaurant.

00:18:28.480 --> 00:18:32.549
If I were opening a restaurant tomorrow, and
I mean this not cynically, but seriously,

00:18:32.549 --> 00:18:36.290
if I were opening a restaurant tomorrow, the
first thing I would probably do is activate

00:18:36.290 --> 00:18:40.539
a phone tree or Internet tree or friends and
say, "Hey, will everyone like post a positive

00:18:40.539 --> 00:18:45.860
review of this place?" So that I'm insulated
from negative star ratings on, on a user generated

00:18:45.860 --> 00:18:50.270
content site. My point is you have no idea
where that stuff's coming from. You have no

00:18:50.270 --> 00:18:54.600
idea if, even if it is a legitimate rave,
if you have no idea if that person knows anything

00:18:54.600 --> 00:18:59.029
at all about dining out, has any frame of
reference, went to the restaurant more than

00:18:59.029 --> 00:19:04.760
once, ordered more than one thing, so I think
that as a lot of, as the Internet offers people

00:19:04.760 --> 00:19:09.999
more and more places to go and get what, what
seems like a kind of broader based review

00:19:09.999 --> 00:19:14.679
of things, I think that traditional criticism's
gonna be seen as more important and more reliable

00:19:14.679 --> 00:19:17.990
than ever because it's the only place you
can go and really trust that you're getting

00:19:17.990 --> 00:19:23.211
an independent viewpoint that has no economic
stake in what it's writing about and that

00:19:23.211 --> 00:19:26.622
has a kind of broad frame of reference earned
by eating out night after night after night.

00:19:26.622 --> 00:19:27.622
There was another question. I'm, I, I forgot
one of your questions. I'm sorry.

00:19:27.622 --> 00:19:35.289
&gt;&gt;audience member #2: Does a hole in the wall
restaurant deserve a four star rating [inaudible]

00:19:35.289 --> 00:19:38.431
&gt;&gt;Frank: I think any restaurant can get a
f-, can get four stars and there are very

00:19:38.431 --> 00:19:42.600
few hole in the wall restaurants, true hole
in the wall restaurants that are spending

00:19:42.600 --> 00:19:46.730
the kind of money that you would need to spend
to get the kind of ingredients that would

00:19:46.730 --> 00:19:51.690
really earn you four stars. But, if you mean
like cosmetically, can a restaurant that is

00:19:51.690 --> 00:19:57.350
not, that, that's not draping its tables in
white linen and and pulling all the bells

00:19:57.350 --> 00:20:00.241
and whistles, can something like that get
four stars? Yeah, I think so. And I think

00:20:00.241 --> 00:20:05.440
it has happened and it will happen, but four
stars is a pretty rare thing, so it doesn't

00:20:05.440 --> 00:20:06.440
happen that often.

00:20:06.440 --> 00:20:10.590
&gt;&gt;female audience member #4: Thanks for coming.
One of my questions is about, it's kind of

00:20:10.590 --> 00:20:12.450
related to what you were asking, actually,
is anonymous critics versus someone who's

00:20:12.450 --> 00:20:14.360
recognizable like you, so there was an article
in The New Yorker awhile back about the Michelin

00:20:14.360 --> 00:20:15.360
Guide and--

00:20:15.360 --> 00:20:16.360
&gt;&gt;Frank: Yeah.

00:20:16.360 --> 00:20:26.210
&gt;&gt;audience member #4: how it's so secretive.
And I was wondering kind of what, what your

00:20:26.210 --> 00:20:29.179
thoughts are on that and if it's more effective,
less effective when it's shrouded in secrecy?

00:20:29.179 --> 00:20:32.159
&gt;&gt;Frank: Right. Well, when I was, when I was
a critic, I mean I, I've done a lot of TV

00:20:32.159 --> 00:20:37.179
appearances since I handed in my, my critics
pass or whatever you wanna call it metaphorically,

00:20:37.179 --> 00:20:41.539
but when I was a critic I never let my photo
be taken in real time. There were some surreptitiously

00:20:41.539 --> 00:20:46.120
taken cell phone pictures out there. They
were old pictures from book jackets in the

00:20:46.120 --> 00:20:48.370
past. I was frequently recognized--

00:20:48.370 --> 00:20:49.370
[clears throat]

00:20:49.370 --> 00:20:54.370
in a city like New York or like San Francisco
where you have sophisticated restaurateurs

00:20:54.370 --> 00:20:59.120
and where the stakes are very high and a lot
of money is, is on the line. You're never

00:20:59.120 --> 00:21:03.970
gonna have a critic who operates for more
than a few months before almost everybody

00:21:03.970 --> 00:21:07.289
who wants to know what that person looked
like, looks like, has figured it out. In my

00:21:07.289 --> 00:21:11.809
first months on the job, many, many times
I would be sitting in a restaurant and I would

00:21:11.809 --> 00:21:17.799
notice, in the sort of vestibule area, like
people walk in, pause, like look at me for

00:21:17.799 --> 00:21:22.179
awhile and walk out. And I learned that what
was happening was in those initial months

00:21:22.179 --> 00:21:26.480
if a restaurateur did recognize me, he or
she would literally get on the phone to like,

00:21:26.480 --> 00:21:30.559
the neighborhood, to the restaurants nearby
and say, "I've got him right here, live in

00:21:30.559 --> 00:21:33.201
the flesh, come in, take a look." And that's
what was happening.

00:21:33.201 --> 00:21:34.201
[laughter]

00:21:34.201 --> 00:21:40.790
Eric Ripert, the chef at Le Bernardin, told
me at one point that not only did he, when

00:21:40.790 --> 00:21:44.460
I was appointed, not only did he do what pretty
much every restaurateur in Manhattan did and

00:21:44.460 --> 00:21:49.200
like do a Google image search and see what,
what could be gotten, but if he saw a reference

00:21:49.200 --> 00:21:55.889
to me giving some commentary about the presidential
election on Nightline, back in 2000, he went

00:21:55.889 --> 00:22:02.299
to the, he went to the network and actually
kind of purchased or as a favor, got the tape

00:22:02.299 --> 00:22:06.130
because he wanted his staff not only to look
at still photos of the critic, but to see

00:22:06.130 --> 00:22:12.880
the critic gesticulating, to hear the critics
voice. My point is unless you changed in in-in

00:22:12.880 --> 00:22:17.750
cities as cut throat as New York and San Fran,
unless you changed critics every four to six

00:22:17.750 --> 00:22:21.990
months, you're never gonna have a critic that
is not recognized by the restaurateur and

00:22:21.990 --> 00:22:27.169
chefs who really want to recognize the critic.
Disguises you hear a lot about because it's

00:22:27.169 --> 00:22:32.600
great copy, it's, it's for, for a restaurant
critic to come whether selling a book or just

00:22:32.600 --> 00:22:36.779
giving a talk and-and tell tales about all
the times they were disguised, it's great,

00:22:36.779 --> 00:22:42.769
it's great material. It's not really true.
It's really, really laborious to put on disguises

00:22:42.769 --> 00:22:46.200
that are convincing to wear them, so even
the restaurant critics who've become most

00:22:46.200 --> 00:22:51.190
famous as disguising themselves, really weren't
doing it that frequently. They were doing

00:22:51.190 --> 00:22:56.559
it; it's not a lie, but it's not really, it's
not, it's not the nightly MO of any restaurant

00:22:56.559 --> 00:23:00.419
critic cause it's just too difficult. It's,
it's too difficult to pull off.

00:23:00.419 --> 00:23:06.360
&gt;&gt;female audience member #5: Thanks for coming.
I've read your book and it's really amazing.

00:23:06.360 --> 00:23:07.960
&gt;&gt;Frank: Oh, thanks.

00:23:07.960 --> 00:23:10.830
&gt;&gt;audience member #5: I have two questions
for you. One: what was your most memorable

00:23:10.830 --> 00:23:15.470
experience as a restaurant critic? And two:
how are you critiquing your own food?

00:23:15.470 --> 00:23:16.669
&gt;&gt;Frank: You mean food I make?

00:23:16.669 --> 00:23:17.669
&gt;&gt;audience member #5: Mm-hmm.

00:23:17.669 --> 00:23:22.570
&gt;&gt;Frank: Well, I'm not, I'm not a very good
cook so I don't, I, I'm very impatient. So

00:23:22.570 --> 00:23:29.169
I, I don't cook all that often and when I
do, I critique my food very generously.

00:23:29.169 --> 00:23:30.450
[laughter]

00:23:30.450 --> 00:23:37.120
But, I forgot your first question, I'm sorry.

00:23:37.120 --> 00:23:39.950
&gt;&gt;audience member #5: Most memorable experience
as a restaurant critic.

00:23:39.950 --> 00:23:43.899
&gt;&gt;Frank: It, it's, it's eating out as much
as you are, traveling as much as you get to

00:23:43.899 --> 00:23:49.409
at times, it's really hard to say there's
a most memorable experience, but I do seem

00:23:49.409 --> 00:23:53.169
to always kind of when someone asks that question
remember early, early on, in the first couple

00:23:53.169 --> 00:23:57.529
months when I came back from Italy and I was
living in New York and I was just beginning

00:23:57.529 --> 00:24:02.549
this particular job, the restaurant critic
job, I was lucky. A couple very ambitious

00:24:02.549 --> 00:24:06.830
restaurants opened just, just as my watch
was beginning, so I got to go to them frequently.

00:24:06.830 --> 00:24:12.440
One was Per Se, which is the East Coast version
of The French Laundry, one is the most expensive

00:24:12.440 --> 00:24:17.340
restaurant in New York; it's called Masa.
And it is a kind of set menu that you go and

00:24:17.340 --> 00:24:22.220
you have for set price which is anywhere from
350 to 500 dollars based on the ingredients

00:24:22.220 --> 00:24:30.539
at that time of year and that's without booze,
water, tip, any of that. And Masa is this,

00:24:30.539 --> 00:24:35.669
it's almost this kind of monastic space; it's
very small. It's Japanese. It's mostly, the,

00:24:35.669 --> 00:24:42.590
the kind of, the, the heart of the meal is
is-is sushi that is made piece by piece for

00:24:42.590 --> 00:24:48.429
you by a su-, a sushi chef, who's just attending
only like probably you and the person next

00:24:48.429 --> 00:24:54.999
to you and maybe one other person. Masa would
open for lunch if they had a reservation.

00:24:54.999 --> 00:25:00.630
And one day I went there for lunch and it
was just me and the paper's wine critic. And

00:25:00.630 --> 00:25:06.009
we got there and nobody else was in the entire
restaurant and so Masa, himself, not one of

00:25:06.009 --> 00:25:12.179
his, not not one of his his kind of colleagues,
was the only one there and we literally ate

00:25:12.179 --> 00:25:16.710
about a three hour meal in which every single
piece of food that we consumed, we consumed

00:25:16.710 --> 00:25:21.470
just moments after he finished assembling
it in real time. And each piece of sushi he

00:25:21.470 --> 00:25:27.179
would hand you and you would take it in your
hand and there was just something so unbelievably

00:25:27.179 --> 00:25:31.049
pampering and intimate about that that I'll
never forget that meal. And having it in the

00:25:31.049 --> 00:25:34.830
middle of the day just felt like especially
decadent.

00:25:34.830 --> 00:25:35.830
[laughter]

00:25:35.830 --> 00:25:38.519
I mean, it was just like the height of decadence
to spend that kind of money and that kind

00:25:38.519 --> 00:25:49.809
of time in the middle of the day, I think
just ramped it, I think just sent it off

00:25:49.809 --> 00:25:50.809
the charts.

00:25:50.809 --> 00:25:52.129
&gt;&gt;female audience member #6: I have one simple
question. What, what is your current relationship

00:25:52.129 --> 00:25:53.129
with food?

00:25:53.129 --> 00:26:02.519
&gt;&gt;Frank: I love food. My current relationship
with food is not nearly as tumultuous as it

00:26:02.519 --> 00:26:08.730
has been in the past. It's one mostly of just
outright love, but I, I still find myself

00:26:08.730 --> 00:26:14.480
still having to be very careful. I, I'm a
life-long overeater who has had some periods

00:26:14.480 --> 00:26:20.730
of very bad health because of it and that
never goes away. It's interesting, if-if-if-

00:26:20.730 --> 00:26:27.340
if-if my book fits in a genre, in any one
genre, it probably more fits in, in, it's

00:26:27.340 --> 00:26:32.239
probably better described as an addiction
memoir than a food memoir in some ways. But

00:26:32.239 --> 00:26:36.379
food is a really tricky thing. I didn't think
of it this until I was fortunate enough when

00:26:36.379 --> 00:26:40.429
I was sending around the manuscript to get
a, a quote, a blurb from Augusten Burroughs,

00:26:40.429 --> 00:26:44.669
who I don't know, but who I, who I knew some
people in common and I sent him the manuscript

00:26:44.669 --> 00:26:47.940
and what he said what we put on the cover,
on the hardcover. I think it's on the inside

00:26:47.940 --> 00:26:53.690
of this, was food was a really tricky addiction
because with anything else; alcohol, crack,

00:26:53.690 --> 00:26:58.480
heroin, the answer is just stop. But when
you have someone who's got a food addiction

00:26:58.480 --> 00:27:02.830
or is an overeater, you can't say, "Well,
just avoid the substance entirely." So, it's

00:27:02.830 --> 00:27:07.360
a much, much kind of subtler challenge and
I think it's a challenge that never, that

00:27:07.360 --> 00:27:10.769
never really goes away.

00:27:10.769 --> 00:27:24.419
&gt;&gt;female audience member #7: Where do you
look for, look to as experts when you're looking

00:27:24.419 --> 00:27:26.690
for criticism on food now? Particularly if
you're going to say, a new city, and trying

00:27:26.690 --> 00:27:27.690
to decide where to eat while you're there.
Where do you start?

00:27:27.690 --> 00:27:31.289
&gt;&gt;Frank: I don't, it's interesting, I don't
have a method. I mean, I, I begin with Google,

00:27:31.289 --> 00:27:35.749
I mean as we all do when we're doing an Internet
search and I say that not just cause I'm here.

00:27:35.749 --> 00:27:40.230
But I mean I just kind of Hoover up a lot
of different things and sort of. I find myself,

00:27:40.230 --> 00:27:44.600
in an unscientific way, triangulating a lot
of different things. Oddly enough, I really

00:27:44.600 --> 00:27:49.440
don't end up looking a lot at Yelp or CitySearch
or stuff like that. And it's not because of

00:27:49.440 --> 00:27:53.570
the extreme negative view I painted a second
ago. I mean, I do think all of those things

00:27:53.570 --> 00:27:58.240
are useful if they're, if they're looked at
and analyzed and in the right way and taken

00:27:58.240 --> 00:28:04.380
with a grain of salt, but there's so much
between blogs, magazines, travel guides, there's

00:28:04.380 --> 00:28:11.080
so much writing out there that you can be
going somewhere, you can do an aggressive

00:28:11.080 --> 00:28:13.960
Internet search and if you really kind of
read through everything that's coming you

00:28:13.960 --> 00:28:18.960
start to, you start to notice points of agreement
and commonality. Like, suddenly like, I mean

00:28:18.960 --> 00:28:23.940
like, certain restaurants at every, at every
kind of point in the, in the cost spectrum

00:28:23.940 --> 00:28:29.039
will just keep coming at you again and again.
And I think you begin to get a gut sense of

00:28:29.039 --> 00:28:34.440
where it is you want and need to go. I also,
though, avail myself of a kind of tool that

00:28:34.440 --> 00:28:37.620
unfortunately everyone doesn't have, which
is I know a lot of food writers, I know a

00:28:37.620 --> 00:28:39.720
lot of people who travel a lot--

00:28:39.720 --> 00:28:40.720
[clears throat]

00:28:40.720 --> 00:28:46.289
and maybe haven't written up their discoveries.
So I work, I send out a lot of emails to friends,

00:28:46.289 --> 00:28:50.950
to friends whom I know that like, probably
have, have been to some of the places and

00:28:50.950 --> 00:28:53.190
so I use a lot of those informal recommendations
as well.

00:28:53.190 --> 00:29:09.453
&gt;&gt;female audience member #7: Thanks for coming.
I really enjoyed your book.

00:29:09.453 --> 00:29:10.453
&gt;&gt;Frank: Thank you.

00:29:10.453 --> 00:29:11.453
