00:50:44.529 --> 00:50:50.849
I was and just sort of literally like kind
of stopping and flashing back and meditating

00:50:50.849 --> 00:50:55.859
for a second before I pick up the pint of
ice cream. I think, I think you just kind

00:50:55.859 --> 00:50:57.990
of have to do that hard mental work all the
time.

00:50:57.990 --> 00:51:06.599
&gt;&gt; male audience member #6: So I was wondering
if you could go a little bit more into the

00:51:06.599 --> 00:51:10.170
writing process that you employed when writing
the reviews. Is it something that after you

00:51:10.170 --> 00:51:14.411
go to a restaurant you would stay up for an
hour later and write down your notes? Or when

00:51:14.411 --> 00:51:19.730
would you finally crystallize your, your opinion
of that night's meal?

00:51:19.730 --> 00:51:20.730
&gt;&gt;Frank:

00:51:20.730 --> 00:51:21.730
[clears throat]

00:51:21.730 --> 00:51:25.050
I would do a lot of different things. It wasn't
always the same, but some of the things I

00:51:25.050 --> 00:51:31.769
did most frequently, I learned over time that
I did like to have some sort of contemporaneous

00:51:31.769 --> 00:51:36.289
notes, but it's impossible to take notes at
a table without drawing attention to yourself

00:51:36.289 --> 00:51:40.760
and I tried texting myself, but that also
just kind of goes on a little bit too long,

00:51:40.760 --> 00:51:44.140
so I would, I would either step outside as
if I were going to have a cigarette or I'd

00:51:44.140 --> 00:51:48.150
go to the men's room and I would call myself.
And I would either call my work machine or

00:51:48.150 --> 00:51:52.720
my home machine and I would essentially dictate,
because you can talk so much faster than you

00:51:52.720 --> 00:51:57.300
can write. I would dictate things that were
coming into my head or descriptions of dishes

00:51:57.300 --> 00:52:01.720
or reactions I was having. And that way I
also knew that if I got home at 11:30 and

00:52:01.720 --> 00:52:05.329
as part of the meal I had three glasses of
wine and I really just wanted to go to bed,

00:52:05.329 --> 00:52:09.359
I didn't have to worry always about writing
things down because they were waiting, they

00:52:09.359 --> 00:52:14.320
were waiting for me to be transcribed on my
voicemail. And the only, and I think it's

00:52:14.320 --> 00:52:17.740
a great system, the only danger is occasionally
if you're just a little bit sloppy as you're

00:52:17.740 --> 00:52:21.310
cleaning out your voicemail, you ruin a whole
night's notes. Like, you hit the three instead

00:52:21.310 --> 00:52:24.940
of the two and you're like, "Oh, there they
go." Luckily, it didn't happen very often,

00:52:24.940 --> 00:52:28.960
but and the sometimes I would get, I would
go home and if I was still kind of alert,

00:52:28.960 --> 00:52:33.540
I always for every restaurant I was reviewing,
I had a file in my computer that I would just

00:52:33.540 --> 00:52:36.640
keep adding to. Cause I mean, sometimes you
have a thought three days after the meal.

00:52:36.640 --> 00:52:41.400
Just call up the file and add to it and those
files would usually grow over the course of

00:52:41.400 --> 00:52:45.559
the five weeks you're visiting the restaurant.
And then when, when it was time to write,

00:52:45.559 --> 00:52:52.119
you kind of read through them and that was
that. You seldom decide what a restaurants

00:52:52.119 --> 00:52:55.630
rating was gonna be or what the review was
gonna say until you finished your visits cause

00:52:55.630 --> 00:52:59.369
it could really change over time. I mean,
you can really, you can go to a restaurant

00:52:59.369 --> 00:53:04.891
one night, just happen across the very, very
worst quadrant of the menu. It could be the

00:53:04.891 --> 00:53:08.910
restaurant's most off night and after three
more visits you can realize, "Wow, I love

00:53:08.910 --> 00:53:14.190
this restaurant," and that was a truly, truly
abhorrent experience that needs, that needs

00:53:14.190 --> 00:53:17.390
like the Russian judges score of the gymnasts
and needs to be thrown out cause it's the

00:53:17.390 --> 00:53:22.519
one that's, the one that's the farthest afield
from everything else. But, yeah, that was

00:53:22.519 --> 00:53:25.089
basically the process. I should probably just,
we're almost at two o'clock so I should probably

00:53:25.089 --> 00:53:26.820
just take one more question. Thank you, everybody,
for coming.

00:53:26.820 --> 00:53:31.789
&gt;&gt;male audience member #7: An easy one for
you that you can answer, I'm quite sure. What's

00:53:31.789 --> 00:53:33.839
the most common mistake that you've seen restaurants
make?

00:53:33.839 --> 00:53:40.810
&gt;&gt;Frank: I believe the most common mistake
that restaurants make is, is their, is their

00:53:40.810 --> 00:53:45.210
immediate public face to the world, whether
it be on the phone or at the door. I mean,

00:53:45.210 --> 00:53:49.700
I think that, I always grew up, my father
used to always say, "First impressions are,

00:53:49.700 --> 00:53:54.680
are vitally important because like, you'll
never, you only get one crack at it and you

00:53:54.680 --> 00:53:58.960
kind of are always trying to overcome it if
it's a bad one." I'm shocked at the number

00:53:58.960 --> 00:54:04.990
of restaurants that don't train or manage
their staff in a way that has them be more

00:54:04.990 --> 00:54:09.440
polished and friendly on the phone and I'm
shocked at the number of restaurants which

00:54:09.440 --> 00:54:13.349
don't have a system in place so that when
you walk in and are standing in front of the

00:54:13.349 --> 00:54:17.710
host or hostess station, your, your first
experience is a positive one. I mean, I, I

00:54:17.710 --> 00:54:22.660
look around at restaurants at the number of
times you see an arriving party stand there,

00:54:22.660 --> 00:54:27.230
kind of almost clamoring for attention for
ten minutes before anybody gets to them. I

00:54:27.230 --> 00:54:32.170
can't, it seems to me like such an easy thing
not to do wrong, but I can't believe how many

00:54:32.170 --> 00:54:37.029
restaurants do that wrong. But I think the
great ones don't do it wrong because that's,

00:54:37.029 --> 00:54:41.369
because they know how important it is and
they know that it's an utterly controllable

00:54:41.369 --> 00:54:42.369
situation.

